<reg_short_dscr>:
This register is used to enable or disable certain mission-mode run-time features within the core.
The NONCE_MODE field is used to allow the DWC_trng to run in NONCE seed mode. In this mode the host must provide a user-defined seed to the PRNG through the SEEDx registers. (This mode is generally only used for test purposes.)
If the ELP_TRNG3_CONFIG_SECURE_MODE build-time configuration parameter is set to 0, the MISSION_MODE bit resets to 0, which is referred to as 'test-mode'. If the build-time configuration parameter ELP_TRNG3_CONFIG_SECURE_MODE parameter is set to 1, the MISSION_MODE bit resets to 1, which is referred to as 'mission-mode'. When in test-mode, the DWC_trng allows access to normally sensitive internal seed values and registers.
When the MISSION_MODE bit is written with a 0, access to private areas within the DWC_trng are made available for testing and qualification purposes. When the MISSION_MODE bit is written with a 1, access to these private areas is disabled. The intention is that, for in situ testing and qualification, access to the secret state portions may be desirable (MISSION_MODE set to 0). However, it is highly advisable that these nodes and registers be non-accessible and secret during normal operations. Therefore, the core should only be set to test mode when specifically desired.
The state of the SMODE.SMODE_MISSION_MODE bit is also reflected in the STAT register through the STAT.STAT_MISSION_MODE field for added convenience.
In order to prevent certain attacks, such as backtracking and spoofing, whenever the the state of the MISSION_MODE bit is changed, the DWC_trng automatically zeroizes all internal state information. If the DWC_trng has been operating in mission-mode and is changed to test-mode, the value used for the last seed will have been wiped to prevent unauthorized accessing to it.
Similarly, when changing from test-mode to mission-mode, the internal state is cleared as well. This prevents an unauthorized host process from loading a state, switching back to mission-mode and attempting to spoof consumers of the random data from believing the core is operating from a random seed.
A consequence of the zeroization is that the DWC_trng must be (re)seeded to begin providing random data again. Thus, any toggling of the MISSION_MODE bit requires the host to execute one of the reseeding operations.
The MAX_REJECTS field dictates the maximum number of consecutive bit rejections that have to occur within a single bit generator before the ring feedback control system dynamically adjusted the frequency of the affected bit generator. There is usually no need to adjust this register. It is primarily for test purposes.
NOTE: It is not possible to both toggle the MISSION_MODE bit and set NONCE_MODE mode in a single write operation because the toggling of MISSION_MODE returns NONCE_MODE to its reset state of 0 within a few cycles after the write completes. Changes to these fields must be done in separate writes; toggle the MISSION_MODE bit first, then set NONCE_MODE mode in a subsequent write operation.
NOTE: Initiation of a random reseed operation (a write of 2 to the CTRL.CMD register) has the side effect of automatically clearing the NONCE_MODE mode bit.
