<reg_short_dscr>:
This register allows the user to monitor the interrupt and/or status contributions of the DWC_trng.
Note that these status signals are used for both polling mode and interrupt modes. Whether they assert the O_irq output depends on whether the IE.GLBL_EN and one or more of the other individual IE bits are set to 1.
The RAND_RDY bit indicate the completion of the collection of the 128- or 256-bit random number.
The SEED_DONE bit indicates completion of a random reseed operation. Because the core automatically initiates a 'generate random number' operation (equivalent to writing CMD_GEN_RAND to the CTRL.CMD register) immediately after a nonce has been loaded, there is no NONCE reseed interrupt mechanism. Therefore, the automatically generated random number interrupt (RNAD_RDY) may be used if a 'nonce reseed complete' interrupt, if desired, when in nonce mode.
The RQST_ALARM and AGE_ALARM bits indicate that the respective reseed alarms have expired and that the host should consider issuing a reseed command -- unless the core was set for AUTO_RESEED mode during the build-time configuration. (The inclusion of the build-time configuration AUTO_RESEED mode may be determined from the BUILD_CONFIG.AUTO_RESEED_LOOPBACK field). If this mode was enabled at build-time, there is no need to react to this alarm because the DWC_trng automatically regenerates and installs a seed autonomously.)
Both of the RQST_ALARM and AGE_ALARM alarms are built using auto-reloading counters. Thus, they automatically re-initialize themselves as soon as they expire. The reload values for these counters are stored in the AUTO_RQST and AUTO_AGE registers, respectively. Additionally, these counters are reloaded any time a new seed regeneration operation is preformed.
The LFSR_LOCKUP bit indicates something has disrupted the internal PRNG. The most likely cause for this alarm is silicon failure or a radiation related single event upset (SEU). If the LFSR_LOCKUP alarm fires, the core zorizes its internal state and ceases producing random data. The alarm must be acknowledged and cleared by the host and the core must be reseeded before it will resume generating random numbers. If the core was set for AUTO_RESEED mode during the build-time configuration, the reseed operation happens automatically. If the AUTO_RESEED mode was not selected at build-time, the DWC_trng must be reseeded through any of the available reseed mechanisms. (The inclusion of the build-time configuration AUTO_RESEED mode may be determined from the BUILD_CONFIG.AUTO_RESEED_LOOPBACK field).
NOTE: If the LFSR_LOCKUP alarm fires, the DWC_trng exits the seeded mode. Unless the DWC_trng is configured with ESM nonce I/O, it will deassert the O_seeded port and assert the O_reminder port. If the DWC_trng is zeriozed through any of the zeroization methods, the LFSR_LOCKUP bit is cleared, the same as if the alarm had been acknowledged.
